explanation:
- OS_ObjectIdGetById: The function determines the conditional branch in OS_BinSemTimedWait. To decide whether the call to OS_BinSemTimedWait_Impl (or that branch at all) can ever execute you must know the possible return values and semantics of OS_ObjectIdGetById (e.g. when it returns OS_SUCCESS vs error). If OS_ObjectIdGetById can never return OS_SUCCESS for semaphore IDs, the branch (and thus that call) would be dead.

- OS_BinSemTimedWait_Impl: The actual work is done here. To determine whether the call is removable without changing program behaviour (dead code) you must know whether this implementation has observable side effects (state changes, timing effects, I/O, blocking) or is redundant. If it has effects, the call cannot be considered dead even if reachable rarely.

- OS_SUCCESS: The conditional compares return_code to this macro. Its value and any associated semantics (e.g. other success codes, multi-value success) determine whether the equality test can succeed; needed to reason about whether the branch is reachable.

- OS_LOCK_MODE_NONE and LOCAL_OBJID_TYPE: These arguments influence OS_ObjectIdGetById behaviour (lookup mode and object type). The analysis needs to know how these constants affect the lookup logic and whether, for semaphore IDs, OS_ObjectIdGetById can succeed under these modes—affecting branch reachability.

- OS_object_token_t: The token type passed by reference to OS_ObjectIdGetById and then to the Impl routine. Its definition can reveal whether initialization/assignment semantics or side-effects exist (e.g. whether an unchanged token could make the Impl no-op) and whether use of the token introduces observable behaviour that prevents removal.

- osal_id_t: The type and domain/encoding of sem_id are needed to reason about which values are legal and whether any plausible caller can supply an ID that makes OS_ObjectIdGetById return OS_SUCCESS. Also useful to check for special sentinel values that force particular control flow.

- OS_SymbolLookup: To determine if OS_BinSemTimedWait is actually dead in the whole project, you must check indirect references or dynamic lookup/registration mechanisms. OS_SymbolLookup (or similar symbol-table facilities) can be used at runtime by other components to call this API indirectly; knowledge of such facilities is required to conclude whether the function is unused.

- OS_API_Init: Initialization or API registration functions may install this function into dispatch tables or expose it to external callers. Examining OS_API_Init (or other registration code) is necessary to determine whether the function is reachable indirectly (via tables, RPC, syscall dispatch), which affects whether it is dead code.

These symbols together provide the information needed to decide (1) whether the conditional branch that calls OS_BinSemTimedWait_Impl can ever execute and (2) whether removing that call or the entire function would change observable program behaviour (including indirect/dynamic invocation and side effects).
